Security Review — The Daily Harvest API
CRITICAL
C1 — Passwords stored in plain text
File: auth.ts:41-47
Severity: Critical

The password is silently discarded after validation and never stored — meaning login cannot verify it either. The login handler finds the user by email alone and grants access to anyone who knows a registered email address.

Fix:

Test cases to add:

Login with correct password → 200
Login with wrong password → 401
Verify passwordHash is never returned in any response body
C2 — No session token issued on login
File: auth.ts:66-68
Severity: Critical

A raw userId is returned with no cryptographic token. Any client that receives or guesses a userId can use it to impersonate any user, since no route validates identity after login.

Fix: Issue a signed JWT with short expiry:

C3 — All mutating routes are completely unauthenticated
Files: src/routes/cart.ts, src/routes/products.ts, src/routes/reviews.ts
Severity: Critical

POST/PUT/DELETE /api/products, POST /api/cart/checkout, and POST /api/reviews/:id require no identity. Any anonymous caller can add products, clear other users' carts, or post fake reviews.

Fix: Create a JWT middleware and apply it to all mutating routes:

HIGH
H1 — Cart is global, not per-user
File: cart.ts:9
Severity: High

Every user sees and modifies the same cart. User A's checkout clears User B's items. This is a broken access control violation — OWASP A01:2021.

Fix: Key carts by user ID from the JWT:

H2 — Wildcard CORS allows any origin
File: app.ts:11
Severity: High

This permits cross-origin requests from any domain, enabling CSRF-like attacks from malicious sites.

Fix:

H3 — No security HTTP headers (missing helmet)
File: src/app.ts
Severity: High

No Content-Security-Policy, X-Frame-Options, X-Content-Type-Options, or Strict-Transport-Security headers are set.

Fix:

H4 — lodash 4.17.20 — known vulnerability in devDependencies
File: package.json:38
Severity: High

lodash@4.17.20 has a known prototype pollution vulnerability (CVE-2021-23337). It's listed as a devDependency with no import in any source file — it appears unused.

Fix: Remove it entirely:

H5 — No rate limiting on authentication endpoints
File: src/routes/auth.ts
Severity: High

POST /api/auth/login and /register have no rate limit. An attacker can brute-force passwords or enumerate email addresses without restriction.

Fix:

MEDIUM
M1 — User enumeration via distinct error messages
File: auth.ts:64-67

The 409 on /register confirms whether an email exists. An attacker can enumerate valid accounts.

Fix: Return 200 with a generic message on register regardless:

M2 — No input length limits — DoS via large payloads
Files: All routes
Severity: Medium

express.json() accepts arbitrarily large bodies. A caller can POST a name field that is megabytes long, exhausting memory.

Fix:

M3 — reviews.ts accepts unbounded free-text without length validation
File: reviews.ts:23-28

author and comment are stored with no length cap. Malicious content (very long strings, control characters) can be stored and later reflected to other clients.

Fix:

M4 — PUT /api/products/:id allows mass assignment
File: products.ts:63-65

The entire req.body is spread onto the product. A caller can inject unexpected fields (e.g. reviews, internal flags) directly into the stored object.

Fix: Explicitly allowlist accepted update fields:

M5 — orderId is predictable (Date.now())
File: cart.ts:97

Timestamps are guessable. Downstream systems relying on this as a unique or secret identifier are vulnerable to enumeration.

Fix: Use a cryptographically random ID:

LOW
L1 — No security event logging
Severity: Low

Auth failures, invalid tokens, and validation rejections produce no log entries. There is no way to detect brute-force attempts or audit suspicious activity.

Fix: Add structured logging at minimum on:

Failed login attempts (email, IP, timestamp — never password)
JWT validation failures
Any 4xx on auth routes
L2 — JWT_SECRET has no enforcement
Severity: Low

When JWT is added, process.env.JWT_SECRET must be validated at startup — not silently defaulted to undefined which would cause jwt.verify to throw on every request.

Fix:

L3 — No package-lock.json
Severity: Low

No lockfile means npm install resolves unpinned ranges (^4.18.2) differently at each install — supply chain risk.

